    "title": "LESSON 9: PERSONAL PRONOUNS",
    "header_color": "cyan",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "German has MORE pronouns than English:",
          "",
          "ich     = I",
          "du      = you (informal, one person)",
          "er      = he",
          "sie     = she",
          "es      = it",
          "wir     = we",
          "ihr     = you (informal, multiple people)",
          "sie     = they",
          "Sie     = you (FORMAL - always capitalized!)",
          "",
          "KEY POINT: German distinguishes:",
          "  • du = friends, family, children",
          "  • Sie = strangers, bosses, elders",
          "",
          "When in doubt, use Sie until invited to use du."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lektion neun"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "010",
    "trigger_word": "auf|räumen",
    "trigger_card_number": 268,
    "title": "LESSON 10: CASES (NOM & AKK)",
    "header_color": "cyan",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "German uses CASES to show a word's job.",
          "For now, learn TWO:",
          "",
          "NOMINATIVE = subject (who does it)",
          "ACCUSATIVE = direct object (what is done)",
          "",
          "Der Mann hat einen Hund.",
          "(The man has a dog)",
          "",
          "• Der Mann = NOMINATIVE (subject)         NOM",
          "• einen Hund = ACCUSATIVE (object)        AKK",
          "",
          "ARTICLE CHANGES:  NOM    →  AKK",
          "Masculine:        der/ein → den/einen",
          "Feminine:         die/eine → die/eine",
          "Neuter:           das/ein → das/ein",
          "",
          "Only MASCULINE changes in accusative!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lektion zehn"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "012",
    "trigger_word": "an|ziehen",
    "trigger_card_number": 315,
    "title": "LESSON 12: SEPARABLE VERBS",
    "header_color": "cyan",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Some German verbs SPLIT APART in sentences:",
          "",
          "an|kommen = to arrive",
          "→ Der Zug kommt um 10 Uhr an.",
          "  (The train arrives at 10 o'clock)",
          "",
          "The PREFIX (an) jumps to the END!",
          "",
          "MORE EXAMPLES:",
          "auf|stehen → Ich stehe um 7 Uhr auf.",
          "(to get up → I get up at 7 o'clock)",
          "",
          "aus|gehen → Wir gehen heute aus.",
          "(to go out → We're going out today)",
          "",
          "NOTE: Flashcards show separable verbs with",
          "a pipe: an|kommen, auf|stehen"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lektion zwölf"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "011",
    "trigger_word": "Schuhe",
    "trigger_card_number": 313,
    "title": "LESSON 11: PLURAL FORMATION",
    "header_color": "cyan",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "German nouns form plurals in FIVE main ways:",
          "",
          "1. Add -e:  der Tisch → die Tische",
          "2. Add -en/-n:  die Frau → die Frauen",
          "3. Add -er:  das Kind → die Kinder",
          "4. Add -s:  das Auto → die Autos",
          "5. Umlaut only:  der Apfel → die Äpfel",
          "",
          "ARTICLE CHANGES:",
          "ALL plurals use \"die\" (regardless of gender)",
          "",
          "HINTS (not rules!):",
          "• Feminine often → -en (die Frau → die Frauen)",
          "• Neuter often → -er (das Kind → die Kinder)",
          "• Words ending in -e → -n (die Minute → Minuten)",
          "",
          "Many irregulars! Always learn: die Nudeln",
          "(the noodles - already plural form)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lektion elf"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "013",
    "trigger_word": "Hand",
    "trigger_card_number": 323,
    "title": "LESSON 13: IMPERATIV (COMMANDS)",
    "header_color": "cyan",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "Commands in German depend on who you're",
          "addressing:",
          "",
          "DU-FORM (informal singular):",
          "Drop 'st' from du-form, drop 'du':",
          "du kommst → Komm! (Come!)",
          "du gehst → Geh! (Go!)",
          "du wartest → Warte! (Wait!)",
          "",
          "IHR-FORM (informal plural):",
          "Use ihr-form, drop 'ihr':",
          "ihr kommt → Kommt! (Come!)",
          "ihr geht → Geht! (Go!)",
          "",
          "SIE-FORM (formal, singular & plural):",
          "Use Sie-form, keep 'Sie' after verb:",
          "Kommen Sie! (Come!)",
          "Gehen Sie! (Go!)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Lektion dreizehn"
      },
      {
        "page": 2,
        "total_pages": 2,
        "content": [
          "SPECIAL CASES:",
          "",
          "SEIN (to be) - irregular:",
          "du → Sei ruhig! (Be quiet!)",
          "ihr → Seid ruhig!",
          "Sie → Seien Sie ruhig!",
          "",
          "HABEN (to have):",
          "du → Hab Geduld! (Have patience!)",
          "ihr → Habt Geduld!",
          "Sie → Haben Sie Geduld!",
          "",
          "SEPARABLE VERBS - prefix goes to end:",
          "auf|stehen → Steh auf! (Get up!)",
          "mit|kommen → Komm mit! (Come along!)",
          "",
          "SOFTENING COMMANDS:",
          "Add 'bitte' (please) or 'mal' (softener):",
          "Komm mal her! (Come here - friendly)"
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
